      "audio": "audio_01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "title": "Three Forms of Quadratics",
      "kind": "concept",
      "narration": "Quadratics appear in three key forms. General form gives the y-intercept directly. Factorized form shows the x-intercepts. Completed square form reveals the turning point coordinates. Choose the form that suits your problem.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Three Forms of Quadratics",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "y = ax^2 + bx + c \\quad \\text{(General)}",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 2
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "Read y-intercept: c",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 4
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "y = (x - \\alpha)(x - \\beta) \\quad \\text{(Factorized)}",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 7
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "Read x-intercepts: α and β",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 9
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "y = a(x - h)^2 + k \\quad \\text{(Completed Square)}",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 12
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "Read turning point: (h, k)",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 14
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 17,
      "audio": "audio_02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "title": "Completing the Square",
      "kind": "method",
      "narration": "To complete the square, factor out the coefficient of x squared if needed. Then add and subtract the square of half the x coefficient inside the bracket. Simplify to get the completed square form, which reveals the turning point directly.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Completing the Square",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "y = -x^2 + 6x - 14",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 2
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= -(x^2 - 6x + 14)",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 5
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= -\\left[x^2 - 6x + \\left(\\frac{6}{2}\\right)^2 - \\left(\\frac{6}{2}\\right)^2 + 14\\right]",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 8
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= -[(x - 3)^2 + 5]",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 12
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= -(x - 3)^2 - 5",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 15
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "text": "Turning point: (3, -5) — this is a maximum",
          "kind": "tip",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 17
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 20,
      "audio": "audio_03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "title": "Maximum and Minimum Values",
      "kind": "example",
      "narration": "For a negative leading coefficient, the parabola opens downward and has a maximum at the vertex. For a positive coefficient, it opens upward with a minimum. The k-value in the completed square form gives the max or min value directly.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Finding Maximum and Minimum",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "y = 3x^2 + 12x + 13",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 2
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= 3(x^2 + 4x) + 13",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 4
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= 3\\left[(x + 2)^2 - 4\\right] + 13",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 7
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "= 3(x + 2)^2 + 1",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 11
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "text": "Minimum point: (-2, 1) — coefficient is positive",
          "kind": "info",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 13
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "If curves have max below min of another, they won't intersect",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 16
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 19,
      "audio": "audio_04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "title": "Discriminant and Nature of Roots",
      "kind": "concept",
      "narration": "The discriminant b squared minus four a c tells us about roots. If it's greater than zero, we have two distinct real roots. If it equals zero, one repeated root. If it's less than zero, no real roots — the curve doesn't touch the x-axis.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Discriminant: b² - 4ac",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "b² - 4ac > 0: Two distinct real roots",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 3
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "b² - 4ac = 0: One repeated root (tangent)",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 7
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "b² - 4ac < 0: No real roots (no x-intercepts)",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 11
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "text": "Use the discriminant to find conditions on parameters",
          "kind": "tip",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 15
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 18,
      "audio": "audio_05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "title": "Applying the Discriminant",
      "kind": "example",
      "narration": "To find when a quadratic has real roots, set the discriminant greater than or equal to zero. Rearrange and solve the resulting inequality. Watch out: don't write p squared greater than or equal to four as p greater than or equal to plus or minus two — that's incorrect. Solve properly using a number line.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Example: Real Roots Condition",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "4(px - 4) = x^2 \\Rightarrow x^2 - 4px + 16 = 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 3
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "For real roots: b² - 4ac ≥ 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 7
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "(-4p)^2 - 4(1)(16) \\geq 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 9
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "16p^2 - 64 \\geq 0 \\Rightarrow p^2 - 4 \\geq 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 12
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "(p - 2)(p + 2) \\geq 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 15
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "text": "Solution: p ≤ -2 or p ≥ 2",
          "kind": "info",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 17
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "text": "Common mistake: p² ≥ 4 does NOT give p ≥ ±2",
          "kind": "warning",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 19
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 22,
      "audio": "audio_06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 7,
      "title": "Solving Quadratic Inequalities",
      "kind": "method",
      "narration": "To solve a quadratic inequality, rearrange to standard form, factorize or use the quadratic formula to find the roots, then sketch a number line or graph. Use the graph to read off the solution intervals. Remember: for less than zero, choose the region between roots if the parabola opens upward.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Solving Quadratic Inequalities",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 0
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "x^2 + x - 2 < 2(x - 1)^2",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 2
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "x^2 + x - 2 < 2x^2 - 4x + 2",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 5
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "-x^2 + 5x - 4 < 0 \\Rightarrow x^2 - 5x + 4 > 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 8
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "(x - 4)(x - 1) > 0",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 11
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "text": "Sketch: parabola opens upward, roots at 1 and 4",
          "kind": "tip",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 13
        },
        {
          "type": "bullet",
          "text": "Solution: x < 1 or x > 4",
          "reveal_at_seconds": 16
        }
      ],
      "duration_hint_sec": 18,
      "audio": "audio_07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "id": 8,
      "title": "Recap and Next Steps",
      "kind": "outro",
      "narration": "We've covered completing the square, finding turning points, using the discriminant for nature of roots, and solving quadratic inequalities. Practice these techniques with past papers and watch out for common mistakes with inequalities and discriminant conditions. Good luck!",
      "blocks": [
